doc.after: In the middle of the 1930s, as the Great Depression came to an end, the U.S. economy began to strengthen.[2] This was good news for the Cessna Aircraft Company as Dwane Wallace (Clyde Cessna's nephew who was a recently graduated aeronautical engineer) decided to assist his uncle in building more modern airplanes. The design of the first Airmaster is credited to Dwane L. Wallace, and the first flight of the C-34 model was in June 1935.[3] Not long after introduction of the C-34, Clyde Cessna retired from aircraft-building activity, leaving the company to his nephew.
